{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013E76eygobih5Zb74qAjon4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The node is running but stuck - it's trying to contact `es-cluster-1` and `es-cluster-2` which no longer exist (were scaled down). The cluster can't form quorum because:\n1. `auto_shrink_voting_configuration=false` means Elasticsearch won't automatically shrink the voting configuration\n2. The cluster still needs 2 of 3 nodes for quorum but only has 1\n\nThe fix is to use the Elasticsearch cluster voting exclusions API to tell ES that the other nodes are excluded from voting, then clear those exclusions, and also re-enable `auto_shrink_voting_configuration`.\nBut since the cluster isn't responsive, I can't reach the API - this is a bootstrap problem. In ES 7.x, when nodes are removed without proper decommissioning, the cluster gets stuck needing the original quorum. The solution is to use the voting config exclusions API to add the missing nodes to the exclusions list, which allows the remaining node to form quorum.\n\nHowever, if the HTTP API is completely unreachable, it likely means the cluster hasn't elected a master yet because it can't form quorum. In that case, I'd need to use the unsafe bootstrap command to reset the voting configuration and allow the single node to bootstrap itself as a new cluster. can run the bootstrap command while the node is stopped. In ES 7.17.9, I need to either stop the pod entirely and use an init container to run the bootstrap before ES starts, or check if I can exec into the pod and run it while ES is stuck. Let me verify the exact version and requirements for this approach.\n\nSince the cluster became unresponsive after scaling down to a single node with the voting configuration not automatically shrinking, the standard recovery path is to use `unsafe-bootstrap` to reset the cluster metadata. The challenge is that this command requires ES to be stopped first, which in Kubernetes means scaling the StatefulSet to zero and then using a temporary debug pod or init container to execute the bootstrap command. The restart policy is set to Always by default, so if I kill the ES process, the pod will automatically restart. I could stop ES with SIGTERM in one exec session, then quickly run `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` before the pod restarts, which would let the cluster recover from the split-brain state.\n\nActually, a more reliable approach would be to scale the StatefulSet down to 0, then run a Kubernetes Job using the same image and mounting the same PVC to execute the bootstrap command, then scale back up to 1. Since Jobs are built-in Kubernetes resources and not CRDs, this should be allowed. Let me examine the resources more carefully to see if PVCs are actually being used.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2564,"cache_read_input_tokens":32905,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2564},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"947c3dad-1117-4c33-a766-a069a9afb2b3","uuid":"73010452-a7c0-4a05-9d73-18ffaee15b76","request_id":"req_011CcP2XLyHhXuFUCbdttSUa"}
