{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Gbo2tUGvqHoAVw3JZAacQZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The cluster was set up with:\n- 3 master nodes: `es-cluster-0`, `es-cluster-1`, `es-cluster-2`\n- `cluster.initial_master_nodes` set to all 3\n- `auto_shrink_voting_configuration` set to `false`\n- Then scaled down to 1 replica (only `es-cluster-0` remains)\n\nThe `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting only matters for initial cluster formation - once the cluster is formed, it's not used anymore. The voting configuration is stored in the cluster metadata (on disk).\nThe problem is that the cluster metadata still has voting configuration for 3 nodes, and with `auto_shrink_voting_configuration` disabled, it won't automatically adjust when nodes are removed. The single remaining node can't achieve quorum (needs 2 of 3 votes) to elect itself as master, leaving the HTTP API inaccessible. To fix this, I need to use `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` to let `es-cluster-0` form a new cluster independently, then re-enable `auto_shrink_voting_configuration` and clear any voting exclusions.\n\nSince `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` requires the Elasticsearch process to be stopped, I'll scale the StatefulSet down to zero, create a Job that mounts the same persistent volume and runs the bootstrap command, then scale the StatefulSet back up and wait for the cluster to recover before adjusting the settings through the API.\n\nWriting bootstrap Job manifest... The bootstrap command reads from the default Elasticsearch config location, and since the data directory is already mounted at the right path, I just need the PVC mounted. But I'm wondering if I can avoid a separate Job entirely—maybe I could scale down the StatefulSet, exec into a container, and run the bootstrap command directly since Elasticsearch needs to be stopped anyway.\n\nActually, that won't work because once the container exits, Kubernetes will restart it immediately with the normal startup process, bypassing the bootstrap. So I need a Job that runs the bootstrap before anything else starts. The tricky part is that the bootstrap command requires a `y` confirmation, but I can pipe that input through stdin to make it non-interactive.\n\nNow I'm thinking about whether to also update the Elasticsearch config itself. Since we're moving to a single-node setup, I could either set `discovery.type: single-node` or just remove the multi-node discovery settings. The `unsafe-bootstrap` command will reset the cluster state anyway, so the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting shouldn't matter after that. But with `discovery.seed_hosts` still pointing to the other nodes, the node will try to reach them. I could simplify this by switching to single-node mode in the config instead.\n\nLet me go with the `unsafe-bootstrap` approach since it's the proper recovery method for this scenario. My plan is to scale the StatefulSet down to zero, run a Job that executes the unsafe-bootstrap command, wait for it to complete, then scale back up to one replica. Once Elasticsearch is running again, I'll clear the voting exclusions and reset the auto-shrink setting, then verify the cluster is healthy.\n\nActually, I need to think through what happens with the ConfigMap after `unsafe-bootstrap` runs—when the node starts back up, it'll read those multi-node discovery settings again. A cleaner approach would be to update the ConfigMap first to reflect single-node settings by removing the other nodes from seed_hosts and simplifying the initial master nodes configuration, then run the unsafe-bootstrap job, scale the StatefulSet back up, and finally verify the cluster health and fix any remaining settings through the API. cluster is formed, `cluster.initial_master_nodes` gets ignored anyway, so the safest path is to scale down, run unsafe-bootstrap without changing config, scale back up, and then fix the settings through the API. The `discovery.seed_hosts` pointing to non-existent nodes will just generate warnings since the voting config now only requires the single node itself. After that, I'll re-enable auto-shrink voting configuration and clear any voting exclusions via the API.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":539,"cache_read_input_tokens":38964,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":539},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"947c3dad-1117-4c33-a766-a069a9afb2b3","uuid":"014aaf3a-3c10-4456-ba26-bb086073ad71","request_id":"req_011CcP2aWGDp1GFEs3BwKZDb"}
